377	\subsection{Reward Model Architecture and Training}
378	\label{5.2}
379	
380	
381	\paragraph{Reward Model Architecture.}  
382	
383	Our reward model handles multiple objectives by pairing a causal LLM with per-objective Transformer heads. We use \texttt{gpt-oss-20b} (medium reasoning) as the base. Given an input (e.g., paper OCR, generated question, task prompt), the LLM encodes it into a fixed representation. We extract the pooled hidden states of the last 50 output tokens and pass it to our per-objective Transformer head, which empirically improves performance as compared to using MLP head. (see Table \ref{tab:reward_arch_choice}). The resulting representation is denoted as
384	\[
385	r \in \mathbb{R}^{H}, \quad H = 2880,
386	\]
387	where \(r\) is the pooled hidden representation of the LLM outputs and \(H\) is its dimensionality.  
388	
389	Each evaluation objective \(j \in \{1, \dots, k\}\) has an independent head \(f_j(\cdot)\) producing logits \(\ell_j \in \mathbb{R}^{C_j}\), where \(k\) is the total number of objectives and \(C_j\) is the number of classes (or possible labels) for objective \(j\). Each \texttt{TransformerResidualHead} first chunks \(r\) into \(n\) segments and projects them to dimension \(d_{\text{model}}\), then processes the sequence through \(L\) Transformer encoder layers. A learnable attention query pools the sequence into a vector \(z \in \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}}}\), which is refined via a residual two-layer feedforward network (MLP):
390	\[
391	z' = \mathrm{LayerNorm}\!\bigl(z + \mathrm{FFN}(z)\bigr),
392	\]
393	where \(\mathrm{FFN}(\cdot)\) is the feedforward transformation and \(\mathrm{LayerNorm}(\cdot)\) denotes layer normalization. Finally, the refined vector is mapped to logits:
394	\[
395	\ell_j = W_j z' + b_j,
396	\]
397	where \(W_j \in \mathbb{R}^{C_j \times d_{\text{model}}}\) and \(b_j \in \mathbb{R}^{C_j}\) are learnable weights and biases for head \(j\).  
398	
399	\paragraph{Training Objective and Inference}  
400	During training, the model minimizes the total loss $\mathcal{L} = \sum_{j=1}^{k} \mathrm{CE}(\ell_j, y_j)$, where $\mathrm{CE}$ denotes cross-entropy and $y_j$ is the ground-truth label for objective $j$. During inference, each head predicts $\hat{y}_j = \arg\max \ell_j$, and the final score is computed as $S = \sum_{j=1}^{k} \hat{y}_j$.
401	
402	
403	
404	\paragraph{Reward Model Training.}
405	We train IntelliReward using the human preference annotations collected in our study. 
406	The frozen LLM provides representations, while only the per-objective heads $f_j(\cdot)$ are updated. 
407	Training follows the cross-entropy loss defined above. 
408	We optimize with AdamW (learning rate $2 \times 10^{-5}$, batch size $8$, weight decay $0.01$) for $5$ epochs on a single NVIDIA L40S GPU. 
409	End-to-end training completes within $30$ minutes. 
410	The Per-objective Head is  lightweight and only takes total of 300MB of GPU VRAM during inference.
